1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,100
Welcome to Prompt Compression and Query
Optimization.

2
00:00:03,400 --> 00:00:07,200
Built in partnership with MongoDB
and taught by Richmond Alake.

3
00:00:08,200 --> 00:00:12,200
Richmond is a developer advocate at MongoDB
and has worked

4
00:00:12,200 --> 00:00:16,133
as a machine learning architect and taught
AI and ML for many years.

5
00:00:16,400 --> 00:00:17,900
Thanks, Andrew.

6
00:00:17,900 --> 00:00:22,500
This course shows you how to combine
features of a mature, established database

7
00:00:22,600 --> 00:00:27,200
with vector search to reduce the cost
of serving a large RAG application.

8
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:30,600
Say you're building
a conversational RAG application

9
00:00:30,600 --> 00:00:33,600
that helps users select a rental property.

10
00:00:33,933 --> 00:00:38,100
A user might enter a text query
for one level ranch on a quiet street.

11
00:00:38,500 --> 00:00:42,233
You can use semantic search to find a
close match to the user description.

12
00:00:42,300 --> 00:00:44,100
Using an embedding of the user requests

13
00:00:44,100 --> 00:00:47,800
and searching a vector database for homes
with descriptions that match.

14
00:00:48,333 --> 00:00:51,700
But the user may also have hard
requirements like

15
00:00:51,900 --> 00:00:55,033
three bedrooms, two bathrooms,
and maybe no swimming pool.

16
00:00:55,500 --> 00:00:59,400
These are better handled
with a more traditional retrieval

17
00:00:59,700 --> 00:01:02,600
by selecting data
based on fields in the database

18
00:01:02,600 --> 00:01:06,100
and explicitly store the number of bedrooms,
bathrooms, and so on.

19
00:01:06,700 --> 00:01:09,633
In this course,
you learn to use the best of both worlds,

20
00:01:09,633 --> 00:01:13,000
a traditional database
with an added vector index.

21
00:01:13,300 --> 00:01:18,300
In RAG applications to retrieve results
that provide an LLM for final processing.

22
00:01:18,900 --> 00:01:23,033
If the retrieve context is very long,
this results in a very long prompt

23
00:01:23,033 --> 00:01:27,900
and can thus be costly where retrieval
to return, say 10,000 tokens.

24
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:32,700
If you were to run a rental comparison
website to search, say, a million

25
00:01:32,700 --> 00:01:37,633
queries per day, and if LLM input tokens cost
$10 per million tokens,

26
00:01:37,900 --> 00:01:41,300
you could be spending over
$36 million a year.

27
00:01:41,700 --> 00:01:45,400
So, to help you reduce costs,
this course, will also cover ways

28
00:01:45,700 --> 00:01:49,733
to keep the retrieved results
as small and relevant as possible.

29
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:51,800
Thanks, Andrew.

30
00:01:51,800 --> 00:01:54,700
Let me describe some of the techniques
you will learn.

31
00:01:54,700 --> 00:01:58,200
Let's consider your rental app
filtering on the number of bedrooms

32
00:01:58,600 --> 00:02:02,400
or bathrooms can be done with a pre-filter
or post-filter.

33
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:07,200
Efficient pre-filter is done
in the database index creation stage.

34
00:02:07,700 --> 00:02:10,800
You build a new index of entries
that match common queries.

35
00:02:11,100 --> 00:02:14,133
So for example,
if you know you frequently get queries

36
00:02:14,133 --> 00:02:18,133
for bedroom units, you can build an index
that includes the bedroom field.

37
00:02:19,200 --> 00:02:21,000
So that's pre-filtering.

38
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:23,233
In contrast, post filtering is done

39
00:02:23,233 --> 00:02:27,100
often a vector search query is performed
where you then apply a filter

40
00:02:27,100 --> 00:02:31,300
to this result to select the sub set matching
the required condition.

41
00:02:31,500 --> 00:02:35,533
Large scale applications may use
both of these techniques simultaneously.

42
00:02:36,500 --> 00:02:39,900
Another technique to minimize
the size of the output is something called

43
00:02:39,900 --> 00:02:44,633
projection, which selects a subset
of the fields returned from a query.

44
00:02:45,100 --> 00:02:48,800
For example,
out of 15 fields of a potential rental,

45
00:02:49,033 --> 00:02:51,800
you may want to return only three of them.

46
00:02:51,800 --> 00:02:54,833
Name, number of bedrooms, and price.

47
00:02:55,800 --> 00:02:59,600
Now, you could implement all of this
operation directly in your application,

48
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:03,000
but the database can optimize
all this operation

49
00:03:03,133 --> 00:03:06,633
for performance and enforce
role-based access control.

50
00:03:07,100 --> 00:03:09,333
So they are best accomplished there.

51
00:03:09,333 --> 00:03:14,100
And another powerful technique
is reranking the results of a search.

52
00:03:14,700 --> 00:03:18,900
For example, after using the text
embeddings of the renter description

53
00:03:18,900 --> 00:03:22,933
to perform a semantic search,
you can rerank the results based on

54
00:03:22,933 --> 00:03:27,200
other data fields such as average star
rating or number of ratings,

55
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:30,433
to move the more desired results
higher up the list of results.

56
00:03:30,733 --> 00:03:33,833
In order to then generate
better context for the LLM.

57
00:03:34,733 --> 00:03:37,733
One final technique is prompt compression.

58
00:03:38,100 --> 00:03:40,933
If the retrieve information
is very lengthy,

59
00:03:40,933 --> 00:03:43,433
seeking all this context
into an LLM prompt

60
00:03:43,433 --> 00:03:46,933
results in a very long, prompt length,
which is expensive to process.

61
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:51,100
To reduce this costs,
you can use a small, low cost LLM fine

62
00:03:51,100 --> 00:03:54,600
tuned to compress prompts
before sending them to the final LLM.

63
00:03:54,900 --> 00:03:58,600
There are many opportunities
to improve relevance and save costs.

64
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:01,200
Thank you Andrew.

65
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:04,300
You will learn all these techniques
in the next few lesson.

66
00:04:04,900 --> 00:04:07,400
You will start this course
by implementing a vanilla

67
00:04:07,400 --> 00:04:10,600
vector search
and end by implementing prompts

68
00:04:10,600 --> 00:04:11,600
compression.

69
